      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0681">
               <p>Born the son of <persName>Hugh Evans</persName>, a minister in the Particular
                  Baptist communion, Caleb followed in the same vocation. After serving as an
                  assistant at <placeName>Broadmead</placeName> in <placeName>Bristol</placeName>,
                  he was ordained a copastor of the congregation in <date when="1767">1767</date>.
                  He also assisted in the Baptist Academy of <placeName>Bristol</placeName>. While a
                  supporter of the Hanovers on the throne of <placeName>England</placeName>, Evans
                  was a strong champion of personal liberty and emerged as one of <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s most vigorous critics
                  in the debate over the declaration of independence by the North American
                  colonists. See <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 366–67.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
